se the complexity of data abstracted from them can be impenetrable to understanding. Linguists are increasingly turning to mathematical and statistical computational methods for help, and cluster analysis is such a method. It is used across the sciences for hypothesis generation by identification of structure in data which are too large or complex, or both, to be interpretable by direct inspection. This book aims to show how cluster analysis can be used for hypothesis generation in corpus linguistics, thereby contributing to a quantitative empirical methodology for the discipline.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aCluster analysisxData processing. 0aComputational linguistics. 0aCorporaxData processing. 0aNatural language processing. 0aQuantitative linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCorpus linguistics.  acluster analysis.  ahypothesis generation.  aquantitative linguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015z978311074296108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2015z9783110438710oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831103931700 cprintz978311035025840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311036381440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110363814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110363814/original  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-074296-1  De Gruyter Mouton Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-076251-8  DG Plus